node.text:
Yep, I know a thing or two about “Streetstyle” Jump Ramping and Wall Riding, so I’ll be hosting and judging the @streetplant Best Trick Contest in front of @subsect on September 23 as part of the 3-Day Des Moines Streetstyle Open. This event is free and open to the public. For more info: @skatedsm.

*If anyone pulls off the first or second trick in this video (featuring footage from ’85, ’87, and ’88), they will definitely be in contention for the special award we are working on for the event. 

Edit: @robxwallace
Art: @jakeearp

node.text:
I mention Natas Kaupas quite a bit in my new book of Skateboard Poems, Natas On My Mind. How could I not? He was a hero, that became a Friend and whose Skating I had a front-row seat to— Skating that will always Inspire me in its Purity. This poem is my brief interpretation of Skateboard History, and how in my view, the essential stuff culminates when in the mid-’80s, walls in Dogtown became waves.

On The 8th Day

In the beginning, they nailed roller skate wheels to a 2x4
And when the waves were flat, they went Sidewalk Surfing 
Barefooted 
This was the first day 
 
On the second day, Frank Nasworthy developed the Urethane Wheel and the Potential for Skateboarding 
was born 
 
On the third day, Jay Adams forever breathed Spirit into Skateboarding  
at the Del Mar National Championships with one explosion of uninhibited and unfiltered passion, creativity, and spontaneity  
 
On the fourth day, there was a drought and Skateboarders converged on empty swimming pools 
Tony Alva caught Air 
And Skateboarding was no longer derivative of surfing 
Skateboarding became Skateboarding 
 
On the fifth day, the Skateparks shut down and Skaters emptied into the streets and backyards  
Armed with Thrasher Magazine 
 
On the sixth day, Rodney Mullen channeled Gelfand and did the first flat land Ollie  
Opening the door forever to a New Dimension 
 
On the seventh day, Stacy Peralta pointed his video camera into the uncharted darkness and Shone A Light  
Where Skateboarding could go 
 
And on the 8th day, Natas Kaupas rode up a vertical wall and Redefined Everything

Photos: Chuck Katz
Natas On My Mind is available at streetplant.com

node.text:
NOT SUPPLY AND DEMAND

Skateboards are Sacred—not generic pieces of sporting equipment. Skateboards have a Heartbeat and a Soul, and not only are they instruments of Creativity and Expression, but they are also themselves canvases for Artists. From the Shape of the Board to the Art that adorns it, every Skateboard @streetplant makes has a story, a reason for existing.

Skateboarding brings Joy, Self-Esteem, and Transcendence to people all over the world. We believe that our company serves a Meaningful Purpose by supplying quality Skateboard products and a Positive, Compassionate, and Inclusive message: Skate. Create. Enjoy!

Thank you so much for your support of our Family-owned Skateboard Company!

Let’s Go!

Boards Pictured:

9.875” Samurai on my OG Powell Peralta Shape, Art by @yusuke_tsuge
8.125” Let’s Go! on a Moderately Shaped Board, Art by @yusuke_tsuge
8.5” Shide Bolt on a Moderately Shaped Board, Art by @yusuke_tsuge
9.0” Samurai on a Moderately Shaped Board, Art by @yusuke_tsuge

node.text:
THE CLOCK STRUCK ZERO!

This poem is one of my favorites from my new book of Skateboard Poems, Natas On My Mind, available now from streetplant.com.

Jamie Thomas  
 
Dothan, Alabama 
 
In the morning, before school 
He would pilot his Skateboard to the local shopping mall 
And for a few hours, he would shut society out 
A singular focus, total concentration 
It was his sweat lodge, his dojo 
A place of deeper awareness 
A moving meditation 
It was discipline  
Not as a demand 
But as a pleasure 
 
Board time was everything 
It was the only time he felt whole 
But in those small windows in-between 
He drank his inspiration from the magazines and videos 
Every moment was one of preparation 
The feeding of a sacred fire 
For the accident that can only happen to those who are ready 
 
San Francisco, California 
 
Homeless and seething in the fog 
Spurned and rejected 
Refused at every turn 
But still always faithful to his vision 
Constantly pushing, constantly seeking 
With courage and willpower 
On a battlefield of bricks and concrete 
He held onto his dreams 
The Embarcadero 
 
San Diego, California 
 
Frankie Hill, Pat Duffy 
Kris Markovich, Cardiel 
They went for it 
Past their limits 
This was the torch he chose to pick up 
To carry forward 
This was the gauntlet 
He chose to go through 
He became fanatical 
Progression and productivity were all he knew 
He tasted blood, always 
The torch became an inferno 
Welcome to Hell 
 
He stood on the edge of the abyss 
All roads had led here 
All signs pointed to this moment 
A commitment, a promise, a pact 
He pushed towards the unknown 
He took a leap of faith 
The clock struck Zero 
His Skateboard broke beneath his feet 
Shattering the barriers of Skateboarding forever

Photo: @jamiethomas | Leap Of Faith | 1997 | @jgrantbrittain

node.text:
Celebrating 33 Years of Non-Stop, Skate Punk Action out of Cleveland, Ohio!

I met @kristiansvitak in the autumn of 1998. He'd been Skating for ten years, starting at the peak of '80s popularity, through the lean and underground '90s. He was of a band of brothers who had never quit, whose Board had never been closeted or stored away in a garage somewhere. I had just begun working with John Lucero at Black Label Skateboards, riding for and helping manage the team. Matt Hensley and I were demoing in San Diego, California, when Kristian approached me and asked if he could Skate with us. I remember it so distinctly, more so than any other time a young Skater had ever asked me the same question. There was a humility and hunger in his eyes that I immediately connected with and a strong sense that I had somehow known him my whole life. Of course, Kristian Skated with us that day, and he was on the Black Label Team within weeks. From there, we traveled across the US, into Canada, to Europe and Australia together, and he became a close friend to Ann and me and a big brother to Emily. Those were some of the best times.

To this day, Kristian is Family, and when we started @streetplant six years ago, Kristian was there with us from the start, representing EVERYTHING Street Plant stands for —Independence, Creativity, and Fun. Kristian has now been Skating for thirty-three years, twenty-two as a Pro, and to this day, he embodies the very best of Skateboarding with Positivity and Love. We are honored to know and work with him and present his new Pro-Model Collection: Skate Rat since '88 with Art by @greghigginsart and @robxwallace.
